article.description: Nick Porter scored 14 of his career-high 16 points in the second half and Creighton spoiled Northern Iowa's debut in the national ratings with a 63-55 victory.
article.headline: Creighton spoils Northern Iowa's Top 25 debut
article.linkText: Creighton spoils Northern Iowa's Top 25 debut
article.story: OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Northern Iowa came into its matchup with Creighton ranked in the Top 25 for the first time. The Panthers left the same way they did the last nine times they visited Omaha -- with a loss. Nick Porter scored 14 of his career-high 16 points in the second half and Creighton posted a 63-55 victory over the Panthers (No. 24 ESPN/USA Today, No. 25 AP) on Tuesday night. Northern Iowa, which hasn't won here since 1996, shot just 42 percent. Star guard Ben Jacobson was held to eight points on 3-of-15 shooting. "This is a game we really wanted to get," Jacobson said. "Maybe we put a little too much pressure on ourselves." Creighton (15-5, 9-3) pulled into a second-place tie with Northern Iowa (19-4, 9-3) in the Missouri Valley Conference, a half-game behind Southern Illinois. "We already had a huge target on our backs by being picked to win the conference," said Grant Stout, who led UNI with 17 points and 10 rebounds. "Now they put a bigger target on our backs" with the rating. The Bluejays won their 16th straight at home since last February. Creighton has accounted for two of UNI's four losses this season. The Bluejays also won 55-52 in Cedar Falls, Iowa, on Jan. 11. "I don't know if we have their number," Anthony Tolliver said. "But we do play well against them. Maybe it's because we have some Iowa guys on our team who really get up to play them." Creighton, 2-of-9 on 3-pointers in the first half, made three straight 3s in the first 4½ minutes of the second while turning a three-point deficit into a 35-28 lead. Josh Dotzler hit the first to tie it, Tolliver the second to give the Bluejays a one-point lead and Pierce Hibma the third to make it a five-point game. The Panthers cut it to 40-37 with 9:38 left but couldn't overcome the Bluejays, who pulled away late in the game in large part because of Porter. "The start of the second half was really the game," UNI coach Greg McDermott said. "Generally that's when we're at our best, and tonight we weren't." Porter, who missed six of his first seven shots, scored 10 points in the last eight minutes to thwart UNI's comeback bid. His finger roll and free throw stretched the Bluejays' lead to 45-37 with 8:18 to play. "I was desperate for a game like this," Porter said. "Coach told me to keep being aggressive. My teammates kept getting me the ball, believing in me, and that gave me my confidence back." Porter and the Bluejays had an answer each time UNI looked as if it would rally in the last six minutes. After John Little hit a 3-pointer, Porter made one of his own. After Stout popped a 3, Porter made a reverse layup. After Brooks McKowen hit a 3 on UNI's next possession, Tolliver scored to keep the Bluejays ahead by six. "We just couldn't get them stopped," McDermott said. "We let them get into a flow offensively. That's why the start of the second half was so critical." Tolliver added 11 points and eight rebounds and Dotzler had 10 points. Jacobson, who made his school-record 110th straight start, couldn't get anything going against the Creighton defense. Hibma and Porter shared most of the defensive duty against the MVC's preseason player of the year, who was 0-for-5 on 3s. "Of the 15 shots he took, I'm not sure how many of them were good looks," Creighton coach Dana Altman said. "We did a good job contesting his shots. Any time you hold him under 10 points, you have a good shot to win." Eric Coleman had 13 points and McKowen 10 for the Panthers. UNI used a 17-4 run in the middle of the first half to take a 21-14 lead. Stout scored seven points and Coleman six during the spurt. The Panthers scored just one field goal in the last four minutes of the half and led 25-22 at the break. "We've been playing great basketball of late," Jacobson said. "Tonight it wasn't there."
